text: Thousands of supporters of the cleric Moktada al-Sadr burned American flags and effigies of soldiers in Baghdad on Saturday.
President Thein Sein of Myanmar signing the cease-fire agreement at a ceremony on Thursday in Naypyidaw, the capital.
A member of the medical staff at the hospital in Ajdabiya, Libya. The town came under sustained attack on Saturday by forces loyal to Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi.
Police officers marched out of the court in the eastern provincial capital of Jinan on Wednesday, a day before the start of the corruption trial of Bo Xilai.
Riot police officers sprayed tear gas on protesters in Ankara, the Turkish capital, on Wednesday.
GROOVY  A Classic Album Sunday gathering in Brooklyn.

Anglers at Pyramid Lake in Nevada fishing for Lahontan cutthroat trout, a remnant of a strain that is possibly the largest native trout in North America. Last year, a fisherman made the first confirmed catch of one of the fish, which was once believed to have gone extinct.
Members of New Yorkers Against Fracking celebrated the governor’s decision outside his Manhattan office on Wednesday.
Judy Rothman knocked on doors for Mr. Obama in 2008 but now, she feels torn between her liberal ideals and her fear for Israel.
Prime Minister Narendra Modi of India led participants during a demonstration in New Delhi on Sunday for the inaugural International Yoga Day.
The Syrian government denied the occurrence of any car bomb explosions in Damascus on Thursday.
Julio Navas, a taxi driver, caught in a hit-and-run incident in his 1973 Dodge Coronet in Caracas, Venezuela.
The Shabab, a militant Islamist group, denied involvement in the bombing of the Jazeera Palace Hotel in Mogadishu.

The police investigating the scene of a crash on Wednesday where a suspected drunk NYPD officer in a stolen minivan lost control and slammed into a woman and her two children on a sidewalk in Brooklyn.
Katsuya Takahashi, a former member of the doomsday cult Aum Shinrikyo, escapes from Tokyo's police department on Friday.
Boy Scouts were forced to march in full uniform at the Gay Pride March on Sunday in Manhattan, sparking controversy.
Columbia University forcefully seized property for its $6.3 billion plan to build a satellite campus in Harlem on Thursday. This includes a gas station owned by Gurnam Singh.
Mahinda Rajapakse, the former president of Sri Lanka, was arrested after meetings in Colombo on Wednesday.
Angela Merkel's election victory is questioned following the removal of her election posters in Stuttgart, Germany.
Festival celebration in the center of Kabul, no casualties reported.
A member of the Chinese military gave a man a free haircut in Shanghai on Monday in observance of “Learn From Lei Feng Day.”
Pieter Baba with an interpreter during the murder trial of Oscar Pistorius in Pretoria, South Africa, on Friday.
Jesse Cruz, in green, and Robbie Blankenship after receiving a marriage license in Morehead, Ky., on Friday. The couple had been denied a license by Kim Davis, the county clerk.
Residents of Luhansk, Ukraine, gathered to collect water on Thursday as explosions could be heard in the background.
A forensic expert collecting samples from a damaged train coach after a series of bomb blasts in Mumbai, Maharashtra on July 12, 2006.
Demonstrators attended a rally against same-sex marriage outside the Rowan County courthouse on Friday.
Tarun Tejpal, editor in chief of Tehelka newsmagazine, addressing a press conference in New Delhi on Oct. 25, 2007.

The funeral of Police Officer Waverly Jones. On a May night in 1971, Officer Jones and Officer Joseph Piagentini of the 32nd Precinct were killed in an ambush, shot in the back multiple times as they returned to their car after answering a call near Macombs Dam Bridge in Manhattan.
Rachel Notley, leader of the New Democratic Party in the Canadian province of Alberta, at the ceremony in Edmonton on Sunday in which she was sworn in as the province's premier.
Paul and Marcia Adler of Brooklyn are fans of Barbra Streisand, who, though from Brooklyn herself, will sing there on Thursday for the first time since she left the borough and became a star.
Supporters of Yemen’s government, at right, holding olive branches, had peaceful discussions with antigovernment protesters outside the University of Sana on Thursday.
The Ayacucho region of Peru was a peaceful haven during the violence from 1980 to 2000, despite the Maoist guerrilla group known as the Shining Path's reign of terror.
Thousands of university students participated in arson at the Union Buildings in Pretoria, South Africa, on Friday.
People at a cafe in southern Beirut ignored a speech on Sunday by Hassan Nasrallah that seemed aimed at defusing tensions.
Four people were involved in planning a workplace shooting in Fresno, Calif, on Tuesday.
Supporters of the Union for a Popular Movement were accused of rigging election results in Paris on Sunday.
Security officers violently attacked peaceful protesters across the street from the presidential palace in Cairo on Friday.
People in Delhi preparing to cast multiple votes in the state assembly elections.
Manhattan transit police harass passengers on newly launched rapid-bus system.
The scene of a deadly police shooting in Brooklyn on Monday.
